50|$|Like all <b>ground</b> <b>source</b> <b>heat</b> <b>pumps,</b> direct {{exchange}} systems indirectly harvest solar energy, by {{absorbing the}} solar heat stored at the Earth's surface. The US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) has called <b>ground</b> <b>source</b> <b>heat</b> <b>pumps</b> the most energy-efficient, environmentally clean and cost-effective space conditioning systems available. Geothermal <b>heat</b> <b>pumps</b> offer significant emission reductions potential.|$|R
25|$|<b>Ground</b> <b>source</b> <b>heat</b> <b>pumps</b> exploit stable <b>ground</b> {{temperatures}} by {{benefiting from}} the thermal energy storage capacity of the <b>ground.</b> Typically <b>ground</b> <b>source</b> <b>heat</b> <b>pumps</b> have a high initial cost and are difficult to install by the average homeowner. They use electric motors to transfer heat from {{the ground with a}} high level of efficiency. The electricity may come from renewable sources or from external non-renewable sources.|$|R
